@ad1992 sorry but I don't see how that would help in this problem.

By **_default theme_**, I meant the theme value that was stored in the local storage from the previous session.

so, essentially what we want to achieve is to know the default theme value before rendering the `App`.  This will allow us to show `<LoadingMessage />` and the default state of the `<App />` to be set to the theme from the local storage if there is any.

So the reason behind introducing the `defaultTheme` prop is to essentially pass theme value from local storage to the `<App/>` component.

```mermaid
graph TD;
    theme(light/dark)--> localStorage;
    localStorage--> Excalidraw_Component;
    Excalidraw_Component--> InitializeApp_Component;
    InitializeApp_Component--> LoadingMessage_Component;
    Excalidraw_Component--> App_Component;
```
> Also lets make a constant `DEFAULT_APP_THEME` with value `THEME.LIGHT`

this won't make any difference as the `constructor` of the `App` component already sets the theme value in the default state to light - returned by the `getDefaultAppState` function. 👇

```ts
constructor(props: AppProps) {
    super(props);
    const defaultAppState = getDefaultAppState();
    const {
      excalidrawRef,
      viewModeEnabled = false,
      zenModeEnabled = false,
      gridModeEnabled = false,
      theme = defaultAppState.theme,
      name = defaultAppState.name,
    } = props;
    this.state = {
      ...defaultAppState,
      theme,
      isLoading: true,
      ...this.getCanvasOffsets(),
      viewModeEnabled,
      zenModeEnabled,
      gridSize: gridModeEnabled ? GRID_SIZE : null,
      name,
      width: window.innerWidth,
      height: window.innerHeight,
      showHyperlinkPopup: false,
      isLibraryMenuDocked: false,
    };
```

### Alternate Approach

Another approach to avoid `defaultTheme` prop from `<ExcalidrawBase />` is to resolve `initialData` and get the theme value from that inside a `useEffect` in `ExcalidrawBase` component and set the result to some state. Then that state can be passed to `InitializeApp` and `App` component as the default theme values.

@ad1992 I have tried this approach 👇

```ts

const [defaultTheme, setDefaultTheme] = useState<Theme>("");

useEffect(() => {
    const resolveInitialData = async () => {
      if (initialData instanceof Promise) {
        const data = await initialData;
        if (data?.appState?.theme) {
          setDefaultTheme(data.appState.theme);
        }
      }
    };
    resolveInitialData();
  }, [initialData]);
```

But this did not solve the problem. The behavior is identical.
Start with a light theme and shift to dark after the app renders.

my guess is that the promise is being resolved after the app renders. Making render dependant on the presence of `defaultTheme` state causes the promise to never resolve inside the `useEffect`. It may be due to `memo` but I don't see that happening since the `defaultTheme` state is being changed.

But overall, I think this idea did not work 😐.  In this situation, the only reasonable thing is to pass the theme as a prop to `ExcalidrawBase` which is how it's done in the current state of this PR.

